<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-07-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-07-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="372" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                        <head><persName>Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName>Mr.
                            Pike</persName>.</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#left">No. 165.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-07-11"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 11, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            despatch of the 22d of June, No. 138, respecting the decline of our
                            government securities at Amsterdam, and also as to your proceedings with
                            regard to the two vessels built at Bordeaux for the rebels, and
                            represented to have been sold to certain Dutch merchants, which are
                            approved. You will already have received instructions in regard to these
                            vessels.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">James S. Pike,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>